model_solution:
To find the area of the hexagon, we can find the area of the large rectangle (containing the hexagon) and then subtract the area of the four right-angled triangles. 

[asy]
unitsize(0.5cm);
defaultpen(linewidth(0.7)+fontsize(10));
dotfactor = 4;
int i,j;
for(i=0;i<=5;++i)

{

for(j=-4;j<=4;++j)

{

dot((i,j));

}

}

for(i=1;i<=5;++i)

{

draw((i,-2)--(i,2));

}
for(j=1;j<=4;++j)

{

draw((-2,j)--(2,j));

draw((-2,-j)--(2,-j));

}

real eps = 0.2;

draw((5,-1/3+eps)--(5,-1/3-eps));
draw((6,-1/3+eps)--(6,-1/3-eps));
draw((5,-1/3)--(6,-1/3));

label("1 unit",(5.5,-0.5));

draw((6.5-eps,1)--(6.5+eps,1));
draw((6.5-eps,2)--(6.5+eps,2));
draw((6.5,1)--(6.5,2));

label("1 unit",(7.2,1.5));

draw((-2,0)--(6,0));
draw((0,-5)--(0,5));
draw((0,0)--(1,3)--(3,3)--(4,0)--(3,-3)--(1,-3)--cycle,linewidth(2));
[/asy]

The large rectangle has an area of (5)(6) = 30 square units.

We also need to find the area of the four triangles. 

[asy]
unitsize(0.5cm);
defaultpen(linewidth(0.7)+fontsize(10));
dotfactor = 4;
int i,j;
for(i=0;i<=4;++i)

{

for(j=-2;j<=2;++j)

{

dot((i,j));

}

}

for(i=1;i<=4;++i)

{

draw((i,-1)--(i,1));

}
for(j=1;j<=2;++j)

{

draw((-1,j)--(1,j));

draw((-1,-j)--(1,-j));

}

real eps = 0.2;

draw((3,-1/3+eps)--(3,-1/3-eps));
draw((4,-1/3+eps)--(4,-1/3-eps));
draw((3,-1/3)--(4,-1/3));

label("1 unit",(3.5,-0.5));

draw((4.5-eps,1)--(4.5+eps,1));
draw((4.5-eps,2)--(4.5+eps,2));
draw((4.5,1)--(4.5,2));

label("1 unit",(5.2,1.5));

draw((-1,0)--(4,0));
draw((0,-3)--(0,3));
draw((0,0)--(3,2)--(3,-1)--cycle,linewidth(2));
[/asy]

The area of each triangle is (1/2)(3)(1) = 1.5 square units. Therefore, the area of all four triangles is 4(1.5) = 6 square units.

Now, the area of the hexagon is the area of the large rectangle minus the area of the triangles: 30 - 6 = 24 square units.

$\boxed{24}$
